<hr>
<article>
<p>
The system of writing numbers in the index forms is known as <strong>indices</strong>.Indices are the plural of index. <strong>Index</strong> is also known as <strong>power</strong> e.g. 10<sup>4</sup> is the index form of <strong>10 000</strong> (10 x 10 x 10 x 10). <b>4</b> is the index or power in the number 10<sup>4</sup> and <strong>10</strong> is the base number.
<hr>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Laws of Indices in Mathematics </h2>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Multiplication in Indices </h3>
</div>
If a multiplication sign(x) is between numbers with similar base, the index/power of those numbers will be added together, while the coefficients of the numbers will be multiplied in the usual way at the same time.
<br>
<strong>In general: y<sup>a</sup> x y<sup>b</sup>  = y<sup>a + b </sup></strong>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
Simplify; (a) 10<sup>3</sup> x 10<sup>2</sup> (b) 3b<sup>4</sup> x 2b<sup>3</sup> 
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
(a)	10<sup>3</sup> x 10<sup>2</sup> = 10<sup>3+2</sup> = 10<sup>5</sup>
<br>
(b)	3b<sup>4</sup> x 2b<sup>3</sup> = 3 x 2 x b<sup>4+3</sup> = 6b<sup>7</sup>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Division in Indices </h3>
</div>
If a division sign(÷) is between numbers with similar base, the index/power of those numbers will be subtracted/minus from one another , while the coefficients of the numbers will be divided in the usual way at the same time.
<br>
<strong>In general: y<sup>a</sup> ÷ y<sup>b</sup>  = y<sup>a - b</sup> </strong>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
Evaluate the following expressions; (a) y<sup>6</sup> ÷ y<sup>3</sup> (b) 10<sup>7</sup> ÷ 10<sup>3</sup> 
(c) 10c<sup>6</sup>  ÷ 2c<sup>4</sup>
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
y<sup>6</sup> ÷ y<sup>3</sup> = y<sup>6 – 4</sup> = <strong>y<sup>3</sup></strong>
<br> 
10<sup>7</sup> ÷ 10<sup>3</sup> = 10<sup>7-3</sup> = <strong>10<sup>4</sup></strong>
<br>
10c<sup>6</sup>  ÷ 2c<sup>4</sup> = <sup>10</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> c<sup>6 – 4</sup> = <strong>5c<sup>2</sup></strong>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Power of Zero in Indices </h3>
</div>
Any number with power of zero is equal to 1.
<br>
<strong>In general: y<sup>0</sup> = 1</strong>
<br>
<strong>Example 1 </strong>
<br>
Simplify the following expression; (a) b<sup>4</sup> ÷ b<sup>4</sup> (b) 6d<sup>3</sup> ÷ 3d<sup>3</sup>
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
(a) b<sup>4</sup> ÷ b<sup>4</sup> =  b<sup>4 - 4</sup>  = b <sup>0</sup> = 1
<br>
(b) 6d<sup>3</sup> ÷ 3d<sup>3</sup> = <sup>6</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>  d <sup>3 – 3</sup> 
= 2d<sup>0</sup> = 2 x d<sup>0</sup> = 2 x <b>1</b> = 2
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Negative Powers in Indices </h3>
</div>
If a number in the index form has a negative (-) index or power, the negative sign (-) becomes ( <strong><sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub></sub> </strong>) and the positive index form of the number is placed under it.
<br>
<strong>In general: y<sup>-a</sup> = <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>y<sup>a</sup></sub> </strong>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
Solve these expressions; (a) y<sup>4</sup> x y<sup>0</sup> x y<sup>-2</sup> (b) 2<sup>-3</sup> (c) b<sup>-3</sup> ÷ b<sup>-5</sup>	
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
(a) y<sup>4</sup> x y<sup>0</sup> x y<sup>-2</sup>  = y<sup>4</sup> x 1 x <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>y<sup>2</sup></sub>  
= <sup>y<sup>4</sup></sup>&frasl;<sub>y<sup>2</sup></sub>  = y<sup>4</sup> ÷ y<sup>2</sup> = y<sup>4 – 2</sup> = <strong>y<sup>2</sup></strong>
<br>
(b) 2<sup>-3</sup> = <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2<sup>3</sup></sub> = <strong><sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>8</sub> </strong>
<br>
(c) b<sup>-3</sup> ÷ b<sup>-5</sup> = <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>b<sup>3</sup></sub>  ÷ <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>b<sup>5</sup></sub>   = <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>b<sup>3</sup></sub>  x <sup>b<sup>5</sup></sup>&frasl;<sub>1</sub>  
= <sup>b<sup>5</sup></sup>&frasl;<sub>b<sup>3</sup></sub> = b<sup>5</sup>  ÷ b<sup>3</sup> = <strong>b<sup>2</sup></strong>
</p>
